'''Amniotic fluid index''' (AFI) is a quantitative estimate of [[amniotic fluid]]<ref name="isbn0-7817-4869-0">{{cite book |author =Tom C Winter |author2 =Sanders, Roger C. |others= |title=Clinical Sonography: A Practical Guide |edition= |language= |publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins |location=Hagerstown, MD |year=2006 |origyear= |pages= 502|quote= |isbn=0-7817-4869-0 |oclc= |doi= |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=KUd6bLOtrxoC&pg=PA502&dq=%22Amniotic+Fluid+Index%22&lr=&as_brr=3&ei=D5hzSL-OHJPgiQGZodHpBw&sig=ACfU3U1KFI2U2NCQmg31qs_QnlaBm6Dw3Q|accessdate=}}</ref> and an indicator of [[fetus|fetal]] well-being. It is a part of the [[biophysical profile]].<ref name="isbn0-7817-4869-0" /> * AFI is the score (expressed in cm) given to the amount of amniotic fluid seen on [[Ultrasonography, prenatal|ultrasonography]] of a pregnant [[uterus]]. To determine the AFI, doctors may use a four-quadrant technique,<ref>http://www.perinatology.com/Reference/glossary/A/Amniotic%20Fluid%20Index.htm</ref> when the deepest, unobstructed, vertical length of each pocket of fluid is measured in each quadrant and then added up to the others,<ref name="isbn1-4051-0380-9">{{cite book |author =Carr, Phyllis L. |author2 =Ricciotti, Hope |author3 =Freund, Karen M. |author4 =Scott Kahan |others= |title=In a Page Ob/Gyn & Women's Health (In a Page) |edition= |language= |publisher=Blackwell Publishers |location=Cambridge, MA |year=2003 |origyear= |pages= 105|quote= |isbn=1-4051-0380-9 |oclc= |doi= |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=YsHwGCYi0YAC&pg=PA105&dq=%22Amniotic+Fluid+Index%22+Oligohydramnios&lr=&as_brr=3&ei=fZlzSMzkA5ykjgHJ1cDpBw&sig=ACfU3U1EbKtOGTTXoR5CcrzbiVepm-BrDg|accessdate=}}</ref> or the so-called "Single Deepest Pocket" technique.<ref>http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/lowamnioticfluidoligohydramnios.htm</ref> * An AFI between 8-18 is considered normal.<ref>http://www.gynob.com/biopamfl.htm</ref> Median AFI level is approximately 14 from week 20 to week 35,<ref>http://www.fetalanomalies.org/Fluid.html</ref> when the amniotic fluid begins to reduce in preparation for birth. * An AFI < 5-6 is considered as [[oligohydramnios]].<ref name="isbn1-4051-0380-9" /> The exact number can vary by gestational age. The fifth percentile for gestational age is sometimes used as a cutoff value.<ref name="pmid20029220">{{cite journal |vauthors =Griffin M, Attilakos G, Greenwood R, Denbow M |title=Amniotic fluid index in low-risk, post-dates pregnancies |journal=Fetal Diagn. Ther. |volume=26 |issue=4 |pages=212–5 |year=2009 |pmid=20029220 |doi=10.1159/000265554 |url=http://content.karger.com/produktedb/produkte.asp?typ=fulltext&file=000265554}}</ref> * An AFI > 24-25 is considered as [[polyhydramnios]].<ref name="isbn1-4051-0380-9" /><ref name="isbn1-4051-0329-9">{{cite book |author =Sylvia Dobo |author2 =Mitchell King |author3 =Lipsky, Martin S. |author4 =Jeff Susman |others= |title=Family Medicine Certification Review |edition= |language= |publisher=Blackwell Publishers |location=Cambridge, MA |year=2003 |origyear= |pages= 133|quote= |isbn=1-4051-0329-9 |oclc= |doi= |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=ETS89YmvaIkC&pg=PT144&dq=%22Amniotic+Fluid+Index%22+Polyhydramnios&lr=&as_brr=3&ei=UppzSKvyGYHsiQGM-oGiCQ&sig=ACfU3U2vkbEgR2-mupYggbnhsdYJ2C67ig#PPT144,M1|accessdate=}}</ref>
==Causes of low amniotic fluid== * Leaking or rupture of membranes Leaking or rupture of membranes may be caused by a gush of fluid or a slow constant trickle of fluid. This is due to a tear in the membrane. [[Preterm birth|Premature]] rupture of membranes can also result in low amniotic fluid levels. * Placental problems Placental problems may cause low amniotic fluid. If the placenta is not providing enough blood and nutrients to the baby, then the baby may stop recycling fluid. * Birth defects [[Congenital disorder|Birth defects]] may occur if the fetus has problems with the development of the kidneys or urinary tract, which could cause little urine production, and it can lead to low levels of amniotic fluid. * Maternal complications Maternal complications may cause low amniotic fluid. Some factors such as [[Gestational hypertension|hypertension]], diabetes, dehydration, preeclampsia, and chronic hypoxia in a woman can have an effect on amniotic fluid levels.
